===============

Heading level 2             &lt;h2&gt; Heading level 1&lt;/h2&gt;
---------------             
</code></pre>

Blockquotes <p> Including multi-paragraphs, and blockquotes inside blockquotes. You can also add other markdown elements into blockquotes, but you'll need some experiments.  <p>This is a blockquote. <p>This is second para.  <p>This is nested blockquotes.   <pre><code>Mardown
&gt;This is a blockquote.
&gt;
&gt;This is second para.
&gt;&gt;This is nested blockquotes.

HTML
&lt;blockquote&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is a blockquote.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is second para.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;blockquote&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;This is nested blockquotes.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
</code></pre>

Ordered Lists <p> <ol> <li>This is an</li> <li>ordered list.</li> <li>In markdown the order of </li> <li>the number in front doesn't matter.</li> </ol> </p> <p> There is a small bug, when you are trying to set the font for the text, the ordered list doesn't work very smoothly. The number's don't show as they shoul, nor does the hyperlinks. <ol> <li>You need to change the font <li>in the ordered list.  <p> Also, you can nest the list items by four spaces or a tab. <pre><code>Markdown
1.First Item
1.Second Item
    3.A nesting orderded list.
    6.Like I said, numbers in front doesn't matter.
1.Third Item

HTML
&lt;ol&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;First Item&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Second Item&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;ol&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;A nesting orderded list.&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;Like I said, numbers in front doesn't matter.&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ol&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Third Item&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
</code></pre>

Unordered Lists <p> Unordered lists can be created by  <ul> <li>adding dashes (-),  <li>asterisks(*),  <li>or plus signs(+) in front of the line items.  <p> The unordered list can also be nested by adding tabs in front of the list. <pre><code>Markdown
- First Line
- Second Line
    - The Nested Line
- Third Line

HTML
&lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;First Line&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Second Line&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;ul&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;The nested line&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Third Line
&lt;/ul&gt;
</code></pre>

Code <p> When you want to denote a word or phrase as a code, enclose the phrase and code in <code>tick marks</code> (`). <pre><code>Markdown
This is the word for `code`.

HTML
This is the word for &lt;code&gt;code&lt;/code&gt;.
</code></pre> <p> You can also escape tick marks with double tick marks when your code contains tick marks. <pre><code>``This is a code containing `tick marks`.``
</code></pre> <p> You can also write code blocks when you add tabs to every line. <pre><code>public static main void(String[] args){
    System.out.println("Hello world")
}

HTML
&lt;pre&gt;
    &lt;code&gt;
        &amp;lt;public static main void(String[] args){&amp;gt;
            &amp;lt;System.out.println("Hello world")&amp;gt;
        &amp;lt;}&amp;gt;
    &lt;/code&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;
</code></pre>

Tables <p> Tables are added with three or more hyphens (---) to create each column's header, and use pipes (|) to separate each column. Pipes at either end of the table are added optionally. <p> Also the size of the cell don't actually matter. <pre><code>Mardown
| Syntax     | Description |
|:-----------|------------:|
| Header     | Title       |
| Paragraph  | Text        |

HTML
&lt;table&gt;
    &lt;thead&gt;
        &lt;tr class="header"&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Syntax&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Description&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/thead&gt;
    &lt;tbody&gt;
        &lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;Header&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;Title&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
        &lt;tr class="even"&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;Paragraph&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;Text&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
</code></pre> <p> You can set the alignment of the text inside the column by adding a colon (:) to the left, right, or on both sides of the hyphens (---). With HTML, you can add a CSS style to each table element. <pre><code>&lt;td style="text-align: left;"&gt;Header&lt;/td&gt;
</code></pre>    Syntax Description     Header Title   Paragraph Text    <p> You can do all sorts of formating inside the tables. <p> If you want to escape the pipe (|) character in a table, you can use its HTML character code (<code>&amp;#124;</code>).

Fenced Code Blocks <p> You can create a fenced code block by using three tick marks(```) or three tildes (~~~). <pre><code>Markdown
\```
{
    The code here
}
\```

HTML
&lt;pre&gt;
    &lt;code&gt;
        {
            &amp;quot; The code here
        }
    &lt;/code&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;
</code></pre> <p> You can add different colour highlighting according to the language by simply writing the language's name by the first three tick marks. <pre><code>```HTML
```
</code></pre>

Footnotes <p> To create a footnote reference, add a caret and an identifier inside brackets ([^1]). The Identifiers can be numbers or words, but they can't contain any space or tabs. The identifiers only correlate the footnote reference with the footnote itself. In the output, the footnotes are numbered sequentially. <p> Add the footnote using another caret and identifier inside brackets with a colon and text (<code>[^1]: One footnote.</code>). You can put the footnotes anywhere except in lists, blocks, quotes and tables. <pre><code>Markdown
Here's a simple footnote,[^1] and another longer one.[^a_longer_footnote]

[^1]: The first smaller footnote.

[^a_longer_footnote]: This is a longer footnode and you can do lots of things.
    You can add paragraphs to your footnote by indenting them.
    `{can even add a code}`
    You can add as many paragraphs as you like


HTML
&lt;p&gt;
    Here's a simple footnote,&lt;a href="#fn1" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref1"&gt;&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and another longer one.&lt;a href="#fn2" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref2"&gt;&lt;sup&gt;a_longer_footnote&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;section class="footnotes"&gt;
    &lt;hr /&gt;
    &lt;ol&gt;
        &lt;li id="fn1"&gt;&lt;p&gt;The first smaller footnote.&lt;a href="#fnref1" class="footnote-back"&gt; &lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li id="fn2"&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;The first smaller footnote.&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;You can add paragraphs to your footnote by indenting them.&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;{can even add a code}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;You can add as many paragraphs as you like
                &lt;a href="#fnref2" class="footnote-back"&gt; &lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
</code></pre> <p>     Here's a simple footnote,1 and another longer one.a_longer_footnote </p> <p> The markdown notations doesn't seem to work, so I used the HTML ones.

Heading IDs <p> You can custom your heading's id by enclosing the custom ID in curly braces on the same line as the heading. <pre><code>Markdown
### The Great Heading {#custom-id}

HTML
&lt;h3 id="custom-id"&gt;The Great Heading&lt;/h3&gt;
</code></pre> <p> You can create a link to your heading by creating a standard link with the number sign (#) followed by the custom heading ID. But sadly, the markdown notation still doesn't work, I wonder... <pre><code>Markdown
[Heading IDs](#heading-ids)

HTML
